#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:8
msgid ""
"Example of Thermo-elastic and electrical coupling (simple nonlinear coupled "
"problem, model object, generic assembly, solve and visualization)"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:10
msgid ""
"This example aims to present a simple example of a multiphysics problem with"
" a nonlinear coupling of a displacement field, a temperature field and an "
"electric potential field. It also aims to compare the use of the GetFEM C++ "
"API and the GetFEM scripting interfaces. The corresponding demo files are "
"available in the test directories of |gf| (`tests/`, "
"`interface/tests/python`, `interface/scr/scilab/demos` and "
"`interface/tests/matlab`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:13
msgid "The problem setting"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:15
msgid ""
"Let :math:`\\Omega \\subset \\rm I\\hspace{-0.15em}R^2` be the reference "
"configuration of a 2D plate (see the geometry :ref:`here <tut-fig-"
"meshthermo>`) of thickness :math:`t` submitted to external forces, electric "
"potential and heating. We will denote by :math:`T : \\Omega \\rightarrow "
"\\rm I\\hspace{-0.15em}R` the temperature field (in |degreC|), :math:`V : "
"\\Omega \\rightarrow \\rm I\\hspace{-0.15em}R` the electric potential field "
"and :math:`u : \\Omega \\rightarrow \\rm I\\hspace{-0.15em}R^2` the in-plane"
" displacement field."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:18
#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:628
msgid "Thermal problem"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:20
msgid ""
"The left and right sides of the plate as well as the hole surfaces, "
"alltogether denoted with :math:`\\Gamma_i`, are supposed to be in thermal "
"insulation. The bottom and top sides, denoted with :math:`\\Gamma_c`, as "
"well as the front and back faces of the plate are supposed to be in thermal "
"exchange with surrounding air at temperature :math:`T_{air} = 20` |degreC|) "
"with a heat transfer coefficient :math:`D`."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:22
msgid ""
"The heat transfer equation for the temperature field :math:`T` including all"
" relevant boundary conditions can be written as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:24
msgid ""
"\\left\\{\\begin{array}{l}\n"
"-\\mbox{div}(t\\ \\kappa\\ \\nabla T) + 2\\ D\\ (T - T_{air}) - \\dfrac{t}{\\rho}|\\nabla V|^2 = 0 ~~ \\mbox{ in } \\Omega, \\\\\n"
"\\kappa\\nabla T \\cdot n = 0 ~~ \\mbox{ on } \\partial \\Gamma_i,\\\\\n"
"\\kappa\\nabla T \\cdot n = D(T-T_{air}) ~~ \\mbox{ on } \\partial \\Gamma_c,\n"
"\\end{array} \\right."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:33
msgid ""
"where :math:`\\kappa` is the thermal conductivity and :math:`n` the outward "
"unit normal vector to :math:`\\Omega` on :math:`\\partial \\Omega`."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:35
msgid ""
"The term :math:`1/\\rho|\\nabla V|^2` is a coupling term corresponding to "
"Joule heating due to electric current, where :math:`\\rho` is the electric "
"resistivity, hence :math:`1/\\rho` is the electric conductivity."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:39
#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:582
msgid "Electric potential problem"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:41
msgid ""
"We consider a potential difference of :math:`0.1V` between the left and "
"right lateral faces of the plate. All other faces are considered "
"electrically insulated. The governing equation for the electric potential is"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:43
msgid ""
" \\left\\{\\begin{array}{l}\n"
"-\\mbox{div}(t/\\rho\\ \\nabla V) = 0 ~~ \\mbox{ in } \\Omega, \\\\\n"
"\\nabla V \\cdot n = 0 ~~ \\mbox{ on the top, bottom, and hole faces}, \\\\\n"
"V = 0.1 ~~ \\mbox{ on the left lateral face}, \\\\\n"
"V = 0 ~~ \\mbox{ on the right lateral face}, \\\\\n"
"\\end{array} \\right."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:52
msgid ""
"where :math:`\\rho` is still the electric resistivity. Moreover, we consider"
" that :math:`\\rho` depends on the temperature as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:54
msgid "\\rho(T) = \\rho_0(1+\\alpha(T - T_0)),"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:58
msgid ""
"where :math:`T_0` is a reference temperature, :math:`\\rho_0` the "
"resistivity at :math:`T_0` and :math:`\\alpha` is the resistivity-"
"temperature coefficient."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:63
msgid "Deformation problem"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:65
msgid ""
"We consider the planar deformation of the plate under a force applied on the"
" right lateral face and influenced by the heating of the plate, assuming "
"plane stress conditions. For linearized elasticity the displacement field "
":math:`u` has to satisfy the following equations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:67
msgid ""
" \\left\\{\\begin{array}{l}\n"
"-\\mbox{div}(\\sigma(u)) = 0 ~~ \\mbox{ in } \\Omega, \\\\\n"
"u = 0 ~~ \\mbox{ on the left lateral face},\\\\\n"
"\\sigma\\ n = F ~~ \\mbox{ on the right lateral face}, \\\\\n"
"\\sigma\\ n = 0 ~~ \\mbox{ on all remaining faces},\n"
"\\end{array} \\right."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:76
msgid ""
"where :math:`F` is the force density applied on the right lateral boundary "
"and :math:`\\sigma(u)` is the Cauchy stress tensor defined by"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:78
msgid ""
"\\sigma(u) = \\dfrac{E\\nu}{1-\\nu^2} (\\mbox{div}(u) - "
"2\\alpha_{th}(T\\!-\\!T_0)) I + \\dfrac{E\\nu}{1+\\nu} (\\varepsilon(u) - "
"\\alpha_{th}(T\\!-\\!T_0) I),"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:82
msgid ""
"with :math:`\\varepsilon(u) = (\\nabla u + (\\nabla u)^T)/2` being the "
"linearized strain tensor, :math:`I` the identity second order tensor, "
":math:`E` and :math:`\\nu` the Young modulus and Poisson ratio of the "
"material, and :math:`\\alpha_{th}` the thermal expansion coefficient."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:86
msgid "The weak formulation"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:88
msgid ""
"An important step is to obtain the weak formulation of the coupled system of"
" equations. This is a crucial step since representing PDEs using standard "
"finite element theory relies on their weak formulation (Galerkin "
"approximation)."
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:90
msgid ""
"Weak formulation of each partial differential equation is obtained by "
"multiplying the equation with a test function corresponding to the main "
"unknown. The test function needs to satisfy homogeneous Dirichlet conditions"
" everywhere where the main unknown is prescribed by a Dirichlet condition. "
"Then integrating over the domain :math:`\\Omega` and performing some "
"integrations by parts (using Green's formula) leads to the weak formulation "
"of the system of partial differential in the form:"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:92
msgid ""
"&\\mbox{Find } T, V, u \\mbox{ with } V = 0.1, u = 0 \\mbox{ on the left face}, V = 0 \\mbox{ on the right face}, \\\\\n"
"& \\int_{\\Omega} t\\ \\kappa\\ \\nabla T\\cdot\\nabla\\delta T + 2\\ D\\ (T - T_0)\\ \\delta T + \\dfrac{t}{\\rho(T)}||\\nabla V||^2\\ \\delta T\\ d\\Omega = 0 ~~~\\mbox{ for all } \\delta T, \\\\\n"
"& \\int_{\\Omega} \\dfrac{t}{\\rho(T)}\\nabla V\\cdot\\nabla\\delta V\\ d\\Omega = 0 ~~~ \\mbox{ for all } \\delta V \\mbox{ satisfying } \\delta V = 0 \\mbox{ on the left and right faces}, \\\\\n"
"& \\int_{\\Omega} t\\ \\sigma(u):\\varepsilon(\\delta u)\\ d\\Omega - \\int_{\\Gamma_N} t\\ F\\cdot \\delta u\\ d\\Gamma = 0 ~~~ \\mbox{ for all } \\delta u \\mbox{ satisfying } \\delta u = 0 \\mbox{ on the left face},"
msgstr ""

#: ../source/tutorial/thermo_coupling.rst:99
msgid ""
"where :math:`\\delta T, \\delta V, \\delta u` are the test functions "
"corresponding to :math:`T, V, u`, respectively, :math:`\\Gamma_N` denotes "
"the right boundary where the density of force :math:`F` is applied and "
":math:`\\sigma:\\varepsilon` is the Frobenius scalar product between second "
"order tensors."
msgstr ""

